I am generally hesitant to try new sushi places.  Don't get me wrong, I am the kind of sushi fiend that will sink as low as grocery store sushi, but a new place? Not often.  And from the outside, and really from the inside as well, Osaka didn't help out me at ease.  The entire place felt like one of those dime-a-dozen cheap Chinese delivery places.  You know the ones.  With the carpet that has been vacuumed sometime this week, but hasn't been shampooed since the previous owner bought it.  The place where they have that ugly gold cat statue that waves its paw at you while you rethink your life choices.  Where the vinyl covering the seats has long ago split, and the wood grain contact paper is peeling from the tables.  Yeah.  That place.  And then I ate their sushi.  I have to be honest; what I ordered wasn't the best sushi I've had.  It wasn't even the best in Louisville.  But, I now realize that was my fault for ordering things I will eat, and not sticking with flavors I like.  I learned this by starting perhaps the biggest fight I have ever had with my wife when, after sampling her sushi, I gave up on eating all of mine and started stealing hers.  I do not know what kind of magic these men are performing with the fish.  I am not sure I want to know.  What I do know is that their skill and talent is far too high to be in such a terrible looking restaurant.  These are the kinds of chefs I expect Anthony Bourdain or Alton Brown to be standing next to on television, telling you how they will blow your mind, rock your world, and change sushi dining in Louisville forever.  Yes, it was that good.  The only reason this place isn't 5 stars is the decor, and the service.  (Look, I get it, I ordered spicy rolls.  I like spicy foods.  I still need more than one refill during an hour long meal.  I don't care how busy you are, you can visit the table every 20 minutes.)
